Date: Fri 6 Jul 2012
Source: News Gold Coast [edited]
http://www.goldcoast.com.au/article/2012/07/06/429701_gold-coast-news.html


Gold Coast doctors say a lack of immunisation boosters could be behind an outbreak of mumps in the city. The extremely contagious disease has struck many adults on the coast and anyone with symptoms is warned to have minimal contact with others. Symptoms include swollen and painful glands, fatigue, and fever.

Gold Coast Medical Association president Dr Peter McLaren said it was rare to see mumps in adults. "It is usually something contracted as a child and can be quite harmful to adults, especially males," he said. "Adult men can experience painful swelling in their groin region and this can cause fertility problems." Dr McLaren said an increasing lack of faith in immunisation meant diseases were spread more easily. "When someone is immunised it is much harder for them to contract a disease," he said. "Many of the adults with mumps may have been immunised but the immunity lessens after so many years. Booster shots can be given but it is up to the individual."

Those diagnosed with mumps will not show symptoms until about a week after contracting the virus. They are advised to stay away from non-infected people for 5 to 9 days after swelling begins. In rare cases, no symptoms are apparent and a blood test is needed for diagnosis. Anyone with swelling around the jawline, neck, and behind the ears is encouraged to see their doctor.

[byline: Jessica Elder]

