[This report gives no indication of the scale of this outbreak, or any other precise information other than that children appear not to be involved.

Mumps typically starts with a few days of fever, headache, muscle aches, tiredness, and loss of appetite, and is followed by swelling of salivary glands. Anyone who is not immune from either previous mumps infection or from vaccination can get mumps. Mumps infection is most often confused with swelling of the lymph nodes of the neck. Lymph node swelling can be differentiated by the well-defined borders of the lymph nodes, their location behind the angle of the jawbone, and lack of the ear protrusion or obscuring of the angle of the jaw, which are characteristics of mumps. In 50-60 per cent of cases of clinical mumps, cerebrospinal fluid pleocytosis occurs. However, clinical evidence of meningitis or encephalitis appears in less than 10 per cent of patients with mumps. Serious sequelae are rare. For example, deafness after mumps occurs in 0.5 to 5 per 100 000 cases. Death occurs in less than 2 per cent of mumps encephalitis cases.

Orchitis occurs in about 25 per cent of adolescent and adult males with mumps and is rare in prepubescent males. One or both testes may be involved, with lower abdominal pain, fever, and chills, and possibly epididymitis. The involved testis and adjacent skin become swollen and red. Orchitis occurs within one week of parotitis and usually lasts 4 days. Infertility is rare even when both testes are involved. Oophoritis occurs in 5 per cent of post pubertal females with mumps and is characterized by pelvic pain and tenderness. Infertility generally does not occur. Mastitis may also occur. Less common complications of mumps infection include pancreatitis, myocarditis, arthritis, thyroiditis, deafness, and spontaneous abortion (see http://www.cdc.gov/mumps/clinical/qa-physical-complic.html).

The HealthMap interactive map of the Australian state of Queensland, showing the location of Gold Coast city, can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/1kAX. - Mod.CP]
